Pre-Game Insights: Kenya will begin their quest to qualify for a seventh Africa Cup of Nations tournament when they welcome Zimbabwe to the Mandela National Stadium on Friday.
Kenya were banned by FIFA from taking part in the last qualifying campaign due to 'governmental interference' in footballing matters.
Kenya have a good record against Zimbabwe with three wins and a draw from four previous meetings between the teams.
Kenya have not lost in six of their last seven matches across all competitions and are now set to win consecutive matches for the second time since the turn of the year.
Zimbabwe were also banned by FIFA from taking part in the last AFCON qualifying campaign and are yet to win any of their World Cup qualifying matches.
Zimbabwe are five points off the pace in Group C after just four rounds of matches.
Kenya's Michael Olunga is doubtful for this match due to an injury.
Collins Sichenje and Ian Otieno are both guaranteed absentees for this match.
Brendan Galloway has pulled out of the Zimbabwe camp due to a hamstring injury.
Khama Billiat is back in contention for Zimbabwe after a three-year retirement.
